tain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert Coventry married Robert Coventry before 1230, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1215":"1215","before 1230":"enne 1230","1230":"1230","England":"England","Cheadle, Cheshire, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1215":"1215","before 1230":"ennen vuotta 1230","1230":"1230","England":"England","Cheadle, Cheshire, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1215–Male":"1215–Décédé","1230–Female":"1230–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1215":"1215","before 1230":"avant 1230","1230":"1230","England":"Angleterre","Cheadle, Cheshire, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs Robert Coventry a épousé Robert Coventry avant 1230, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1215–Male":"1215–Verstorben","1230–Female":"1230–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1215":"1215","before 1230":"vor 1230","1230":"1230","England":"England","Cheadle, Cheshire, Staffo